In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October as National Breast Cancer Awareness Month. He acknowledges the pain and hardship caused by breast cancer and honors those who have lost their lives to the disease. He emphasizes the importance of early detection and treatment and encourages women to find out if they are at increased risk and to learn more about recommended screenings. President Obama highlights the progress made in diagnosing and treating breast cancer and mentions ongoing research efforts. He also mentions the Affordable Care Act, which has expanded access to preventive services for women. The article concludes by calling for solidarity with breast cancer survivors and a commitment to raising awareness and advancing research efforts.